    <div class="formCard" id="multiprinter" 
         style="border-color: rgba(99,102,241,.40); background: rgba(99,102,241,.05); scroll-margin-top: 20px;">
        <h2 style="margin-top: 0;">📡 MQTT Page: Printers & Relay (Multi-Printer)</h2>
        <div style="color: var(--muted); line-height: 1.8;">
            <p>
                <strong>Filament Tracker v2.0</strong> introduces <strong>multi-printer support</strong>! You can now
                connect to multiple BambuLab printers simultaneously, monitor them independently, and manage per-printer
                settings. Perfect for printer farms, hobbyists with multiple machines, or maker spaces.
            </p>

            <h3>🎯 What's New:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Concurrent Connections</strong> - Connect to multiple printers at the same time</li>
                <li><strong>Independent Management</strong> - Each printer has its own connection, status, and settings
                </li>
                <li><strong>Per-Printer MQTT Logs</strong> - Filter message log by specific printer or view all</li>
                <li><strong>MQTT Relay Server</strong> - Broadcast from multiple printers to external devices</li>
                <li><strong>Per-Printer AMS Sync</strong> - AMS auto-weight updates work independently per printer</li>
                <li><strong>Connection Status</strong> - Visual indicators show which printers are connected</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>📖 Getting Started with Multi-Printer:</h3>

            <h4>Step 1: Add Your Printers</h4>
            <ol>
                <li>Open the <strong>"📡 MQTT"</strong> page from the top navigation</li>
                <li>Click <strong>"➕ Add Printer"</strong> button</li>
                <li>Fill in the printer information:
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Name:</strong> Friendly identifier (e.g., "X1 Carbon - Office", "P1S - Garage")</li>
                        <li><strong>IP Address:</strong> Found in printer's <em>Settings → Network</em></li>
                        <li><strong>Access Code:</strong> 8-character code from <em>Settings → Network → Access Code</em>
                        </li>
                        <li><strong>Serial Number:</strong> Found in <em>Settings → Device</em> (starts with 01S00C or
                            01P00A)
                        </li>
                        <li><strong>Location (optional):</strong> Physical location for organization</li>
                        <li><strong>Color:</strong> Choose a color to visually identify this printer</li>
                        <li><strong>Enable:</strong> Check to make this printer available for connection</li>
                        <li><strong>Set as Default:</strong> Mark this as your primary printer (shows in live view)</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>Click <strong>"💾 Save Printer"</strong></li>
                <li>Repeat for all your printers!</li>
            </ol>

            <h4>Step 2: Connect to Your Printers</h4>
            <ol>
                <li>On the <strong>MQTT</strong> page, click a printer from the list to select it</li>
                <li>Scroll to the <strong>"🔌 Connection"</strong> section</li>
                <li>Configure AMS auto-update settings (applies to this printer):
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Auto-update spool weight from AMS</strong> - Enable automatic weight sync</li>
                        <li><strong>Only decrease weight (recommended)</strong> - AMS can only reduce weight, never add
                            back
                        </li>
                        <li><strong>Two-way sync</strong> - AMS value always wins in both directions</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>Click <strong>"🔌 Connect"</strong> button</li>
                <li>Wait for <strong>"✅ Successfully connected!"</strong> message</li>
                <li>Repeat for other printers you want to monitor</li>
            </ol>

            <p><strong>💡 Pro Tip:</strong> You can connect to multiple printers at once! Each maintains its own
                independent connection and status.</p>

            <h4>Step 3: MQTT Relay Server (Optional)</h4>
            <p>
                The MQTT relay allows external devices (ESP32, Home Assistant, etc.) to receive messages from your
                printers without connecting directly to them. This reduces load on the printer's MQTT broker.
            </p>

            <ol>
                <li>Ensure at least one printer is connected</li>
                <li>In the <strong>"🔄 MQTT Relay Server"</strong> section:
                    <ul>
                        <li>Check <strong>"Enable MQTT Relay Server"</strong></li>
                        <li><strong>Relay Port:</strong> Default is 1883 (change if port is in use)</li>
                        <li><strong>Username/Password (optional):</strong> Add authentication for security</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>Click <strong>"💾 Save Relay Settings"</strong></li>
                <li>Your relay server is now broadcasting messages from all connected printers!</li>
            </ol>

            <p><strong>Topic Structure:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li><code>device/{printerId}/report</code> - Messages from a specific printer</li>
                <li><code>device/+/report</code> - All printers (wildcard subscription)</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>ESP32 Configuration Example:</strong></p>
            <pre style="background: #0d1117; padding: 12px; border-radius: 8px; color: #e6edf3; overflow-x: auto; font-size: 12px;">
const char* mqtt_server = "192.168.1.100";  // Your server's IP
const int mqtt_port = 1883;
const char* mqtt_user = "your_username";     // If auth enabled
const char* mqtt_pass = "your_password";

client.subscribe("device/+/report");  // Subscribe to all printers
            </pre>

            <h4>Step 4: MQTT Message Log Filtering</h4>
            <p>
                The <strong>"📡 MQTT Message Log"</strong> section shows real-time messages from your printers. Use the
                dropdown filter to:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>All Printers</strong> - See messages from all connected printers</li>
                <li><strong>Specific Printer</strong> - Filter to show only one printer's messages</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                Each message includes a <strong>[Printer Name]</strong> badge so you can identify the source at a glance.
            </p>

            <h3>🔧 Managing Multiple Printers:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Connection Indicators:</strong> Each printer shows "● Connected" (green) or "○ Not connected"
                    (gray)
                </li>
                <li><strong>Edit Printers:</strong> Click the ✏️ button to modify printer settings</li>
                <li><strong>Delete Printers:</strong> Click the 🗑️ button (requires confirmation)</li>
                <li><strong>Enable/Disable:</strong> Toggle the "Enable this printer" checkbox when editing</li>
                <li><strong>Default Printer:</strong> Set which printer shows in the Live View widget (only one default
                    allowed)
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h3>🌟 Multi-Printer Workflows:</h3>

            <h4>Workflow 1: Monitor a Printer Farm</h4>
            <ol>
                <li>Add all your printers on the MQTT page</li>
                <li>Enable the printers you want to monitor</li>
                <li>Connect to each printer you want to track</li>
                <li>View connection status for all printers in the printer list</li>
                <li>Use MQTT log filter to check messages from specific printers</li>
                <li>Each printer's AMS data is tracked independently</li>
            </ol>

            <h4>Workflow 2: MQTT Relay for Home Automation</h4>
            <ol>
                <li>Connect to all printers you want to monitor</li>
                <li>Enable MQTT Relay Server</li>
                <li>Configure port and optional authentication</li>
                <li>Your ESP32/Home Assistant connects to this relay server</li>
                <li>Subscribe to <code>device/+/report</code> to receive from all printers</li>
                <li>Or subscribe to <code>device/1/report</code> for a specific printer</li>
                <li>Messages are automatically relayed from all connected printers</li>
            </ol>

            <h4>Workflow 3: Per-Printer AMS Weight Sync</h4>
            <ol>
                <li>Connect to all printers with AMS units</li>
                <li>Enable "Auto-update spool weight from AMS" for each printer connection</li>
                <li>Choose sync mode (one-way recommended)</li>
                <li>Go to <strong>AMS Page</strong> and link spools to AMS slots (requires tag UID)</li>
                <li>Weights automatically update from each printer's AMS independently</li>
                <li>Each printer can have different sync settings</li>
            </ol>

            <h3>❓ Common Questions:</h3>

            <p><strong>Q: Can I connect to multiple printers at the same time?</strong></p>
            <p>A: Yes! v2.0 supports concurrent connections to multiple printers. Each operates independently.</p>

            <p><strong>Q: Do all printers share the same settings?</strong></p>
            <p>A: No. Each printer has independent connection settings and AMS auto-update configuration.</p>

            <p><strong>Q: Can the MQTT relay handle multiple printers?</strong></p>
            <p>A: Yes! The relay server broadcasts messages from all connected printers. External devices can subscribe
                to specific printers or all printers using MQTT wildcards.</p>

            <p><strong>Q: Will the Live View show all printers?</strong></p>
            <p>A: Currently, the Live View shows the default printer (marked with ⭐). Multi-printer Live View with grid
                layout is coming in a future update.</p>

            <p><strong>Q: Can I have different AMS auto-update settings per printer?</strong></p>
            <p>A: Currently, AMS auto-update settings are global and apply to all connected printers. Per-printer settings
                are planned for a future update.</p>

            <p><strong>Q: What happens if one printer disconnects?</strong></p>
            <p>A: Other printers remain connected. Each connection is independent. The disconnected printer will show "○
                Not connected" status.</p>

        </div>
        @backToTop
    </div>

    <div class="formCard" id="livetracker" style="scroll-margin-top: 20px;">
        <h2 style="margin-top: 0;">📊 Live Tracking Widget</h2>
        <div style="color: var(--muted); line-height: 1.8;">
            <p>
                The <strong>Live Tracking</strong> widget in the top area provides real-time monitoring of your
                BambuLab 3D printer status.
                See print progress, time remaining, and layer information at a glance without opening Bambu Studio!
            </p>

            <h3>Features:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Real-Time Updates</strong> - Direct MQTT connection to your printer for instant status
                    updates
                </li>
                <li><strong>Print Progress</strong> - Large percentage display with animated progress bar</li>
                <li><strong>Time Tracking</strong> - See both time elapsed and time remaining</li>
                <li><strong>Layer Counter</strong> - Current layer / Total layers display</li>
                <li><strong>File Name</strong> - Shows the current G-code file being printed</li>
                <li><strong>AMS Overview</strong> - All AMS slots shown with color swatch, filament type, and sub-brand
                    (e.g. "PLA · Matte")
                </li>
                <li><strong>Connection Status</strong> - Visual indicator (green pulsing dot) when connected</li>
                <li><strong>Idle Detection</strong> - Shows "Printer Idle" when connected but not printing</li>
                <li><strong>Always Visible</strong> - Widget stays visible above page content on all pages</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Setting Up Live Tracking:</h3>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Find Your Printer Information</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>On your BambuLab printer touchscreen, go to <strong>Settings → Network</strong></li>
                        <li>Note your printer's <strong>IP Address</strong> (e.g., 192.168.1.100)</li>
                        <li>Find your <strong>Access Code</strong> (8-digit code under Settings → Network → Access Code)
                        </li>
                        <li>Go to <strong>Settings → Device</strong> to find your <strong>Serial Number</strong> (starts
                            with 01S00C or 01P00A)
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </li>

                <li><strong>Configure in Filament Tracker</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Open the <strong>📡 MQTT</strong> page</li>
                        <li>Add your printer (name, IP, access code, serial number)</li>
                        <li>Select the printer card</li>
                        <li>Click <strong>"🧪 Test Connection"</strong> to verify access</li>
                        <li>Click <strong>"🔌 Connect"</strong> to start live tracking</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>

                <li><strong>Verify Connection</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Look at the Live Tracking widget in the navigation bar</li>
                        <li>You should see a green pulsing dot with "Connected" status</li>
                        <li>If connected but not printing, it will show "Printer Idle" with a sleep emoji</li>
                        <li>Start a print to see real-time progress updates!</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
            </ol>

            <h3>Understanding the Display:</h3>
            <p><strong>When Connected and Idle:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Green pulsing dot + "Connected" text</li>
                <li>💤 "Printer Idle" message</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>When Printing:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Green pulsing dot + "Connected" text</li>
                <li>Large progress percentage (e.g., "47%")</li>
                <li>Animated blue progress bar showing completion</li>
                <li><strong>⏱️ Time:</strong> Shows "1h 23m / 45m" (elapsed / remaining)</li>
                <li><strong>📏 Layer:</strong> Shows "142 / 387" (current / total)</li>
                <li><strong>📄 File:</strong> Shows the G-code filename (truncated if long)</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>When Disconnected:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Gray dot + "Disconnected" text</li>
                <li>"Configure in Settings" message</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Connection Requirements:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Network Access</strong> - Your computer/server and printer must be on the same network</li>
                <li><strong>Port 8883</strong> - MQTT over TLS port must not be blocked by firewall</li>
                <li><strong>Local Mode</strong> - Printer must be accessible via local IP (LAN mode enabled)</li>
                <li><strong>Access Code</strong> - Must be enabled on the printer (Settings → Network)</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Troubleshooting:</h3>
            <p><strong>Problem: Connection fails with "BadUserNameOrPassword"</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Double-check your Access Code - it must be exactly 8 characters</li>
                <li>Verify Access Code is enabled on the printer</li>
                <li>Try regenerating the Access Code on the printer and updating in settings</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Problem: Connection timeout or "Connection failed"</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Verify printer IP address is correct (check printer network settings)</li>
                <li>Ping the printer IP from your computer: <code>ping [printer-ip]</code></li>
                <li>Ensure both devices are on the same network (not guest network)</li>
                <li>Check if firewall is blocking port 8883</li>
                <li>Try restarting the printer's network connection</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Problem: Wrong serial number</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Serial number format should be 01S00C... (X1C) or 01P00A... (P1/A1 series)</li>
                <li>Check Settings → Device on the printer touchscreen</li>
                <li>Serial number is case-sensitive - copy it exactly</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Problem: Connection drops frequently</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Check WiFi signal strength on printer</li>
                <li>Consider switching printer to Ethernet connection</li>
                <li>Router may be dropping idle connections - configure longer timeout</li>
                <li>The app will auto-reconnect every 5 seconds after disconnect</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Technical Details:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Protocol:</strong> MQTT over TLS (port 8883)</li>
                <li><strong>Updates:</strong> Real-time as printer reports (typically every 1-2 seconds during print)
                </li>
                <li><strong>Security:</strong> Encrypted connection with self-signed certificates (standard for
                    BambuLab)
                </li>
                <li><strong>Connection Type:</strong> Direct local connection (no cloud required)</li>
                <li><strong>Auto-Reconnect:</strong> Attempts reconnection every 5 seconds if disconnected</li>
                <li><strong>Persistence:</strong> Settings saved to database, auto-connects on app startup</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Supported Printers:</h3>
            <p>The Live Tracking feature works with all BambuLab printers that support MQTT:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>✅ X1 Carbon</li>
                <li>✅ X1</li>
                <li>✅ P1S</li>
                <li>✅ P1P</li>
                <li>✅ A1 Series</li>
                <li>✅ A1 Mini</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Privacy & Security:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Local Connection Only</strong> - All communication stays on your local network</li>
                <li><strong>No Cloud Services</strong> - Does not connect to BambuLab cloud or any external services
                </li>
                <li><strong>Secure Storage</strong> - Access code encrypted in local SQLite database</li>
                <li><strong>Read-Only</strong> - Cannot send commands or control your printer</li>
                <li><strong>No Data Collection</strong> - Print data stays on your device</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Benefits:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>✅ <strong>Monitor from anywhere</strong> - Check print status without going to the printer</li>
                <li>✅ <strong>Multi-page tracking</strong> - Progress visible while browsing inventory or calculator
                </li>
                <li>✅ <strong>No browser required</strong> - Better than opening Bambu Studio web interface</li>
                <li>✅ <strong>Lightweight</strong> - Minimal network overhead</li>
                <li>✅ <strong>Reliable</strong> - Direct MQTT connection, no polling delays</li>
                <li>✅ <strong>Always up-to-date</strong> - Real-time updates as printer reports status</li>
            </ul>

            <p>
                <em>💡 Pro Tips:</em>
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Set a static IP for your printer in your router settings to prevent IP changes</li>
                <li>Keep the Access Code secure - it allows read access to printer status</li>
                <li>Use the Test Connection button before saving to verify all details are correct</li>
                <li>The connection persists across app restarts - no need to reconnect manually</li>
                <li>Widget collapses on mobile screens to save space but remains accessible</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        @backToTop
    </div>

    <div class="formCard" id="ams" style="scroll-margin-top: 20px;">
        <h2 style="margin-top: 0;">🎞️ AMS Slot Management</h2>
        <div style="color: var(--muted); line-height: 1.8;">
            <p>
                When your printer is connected via MQTT, the app automatically reads the state of all
                <strong>AMS (Automatic Material System)</strong> slots and displays them in the Live Tracking widget.
            </p>

            <h3>What is Shown per AMS Slot:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Color Swatch</strong> - A live color preview pulled directly from the printer's reported
                    RRGGBB value
                </li>
                <li><strong>Filament Type</strong> - The material type reported by the spool tag (e.g., PLA, PETG, ABS,
                    TPU)
                </li>
                <li><strong>Sub-Brand / Variant</strong> - The filament sub-brand or finish reported by the tag (e.g.,
                    Matte, Silk, CF, Basic)
                </li>
                <li><strong>Remaining %</strong> - Approximate percentage of filament left on the spool</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>How the Type / Sub-Brand is Displayed:</h3>
            <p>
                Each slot shows the type and sub-brand on separate lines so you can immediately see exactly what is
                loaded —
                for example <em>"PLA"</em> on the first line and <em>"Matte"</em> on the second, rather than the
                previously incorrect "PLA PLA" display.
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>If the sub-brand is empty or identical to the type, only the type is shown</li>
                <li>An empty slot shows "Empty" in muted text</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Linking a Slot to Your Inventory:</h3>
            <ol>
                <li>Go to the <strong>AMS</strong> page</li>
                <li>Find the slot whose filament you want to track</li>
                <li>Use the <strong>"Link to inventory…"</strong> dropdown to select the matching spool from your
                    inventory
                </li>
                <li>Click <strong>"💾 Save link"</strong> — the app stores the spool's RFID UUID so it
                    recognises this spool automatically next time it is inserted.
                    Important: automatic detection and AMS auto-weight updates are performed using the spool's
                    RFID tag UID (`tag_uid`) only. The printer's `tray_uuid` is only a location identifier and is
                    not used for automatic matching to inventory. This prevents incorrect matches when a new
                    untagged spool is placed into a slot that previously had another spool linked.
                </li>
            </ol>
            <p>
                Once a slot is linked, the AMS page shows both the <strong>AMS %</strong> and the current
                <strong>inventory weight</strong> side by side so you can spot discrepancies at a glance.
                A linked slot also enables the AMS Auto-Weight Sync feature described in the next section.
            </p>

            <h3>Tips for AMS Use:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Always use NFC-tagged Bambu Lab spools or properly tag refill spools for accurate type/sub-brand
                    reporting
                </li>
                <li>Non-tagged spools may show empty type/sub-brand fields</li>
                <li>The remaining % is an estimate from the spool tag — weigh spools manually for precision</li>
                <li>Linking a spool once is enough — the RFID UUID is permanent and the app will auto-detect it in
                    future sessions
                </li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        @backToTop
    </div>

