    <div class="formCard" id="amssync"
         style="border-color: rgba(34,197,94,.30); background: rgba(34,197,94,.04); scroll-margin-top: 20px;">
        <h2 style="margin-top: 0;">🔄 AMS Auto-Weight Sync</h2>
        <div style="color: var(--muted); line-height: 1.8;">
            <p>
                The <strong>AMS Auto-Weight Sync</strong> feature automatically keeps your inventory up to date by
                reading the remaining filament percentage from each AMS slot's RFID chip and writing it back to the
                matching spool in your inventory — without you having to weigh or record anything manually after a
                print.
            </p>

            <h3>Prerequisites:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>A printer must be <strong>connected</strong> from the <strong>MQTT</strong> page
                </li>
                <li>The spool must be a <strong>Bambu Lab RFID-tagged</strong> spool (the tag reports the remaining %)
                </li>
                <li>The slot must be <strong>linked to a spool in your inventory</strong> via the AMS page</li>
                <li>The linked spool must have a <strong>Total Weight</strong> set (e.g. 1000 g) so the % can be
                    converted to grams
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h3>How to Enable It:</h3>
            <ol>
                <li>Go to <strong>MQTT</strong></li>
                <li>Select the printer you want to configure</li>
                <li>Check <strong>"Auto-update spool weight from AMS"</strong></li>
                <li>Decide on the <strong>"Only decrease"</strong> sub-option (see below)</li>
                <li>Click <strong>"💾 Save Settings"</strong> (then connect if needed)</li>
            </ol>

            <h3>How the Weight is Calculated:</h3>
            <p>Every time the printer sends an AMS message the app:</p>
            <ol>
                <li>Reads the <code>remain</code> value for each slot (0 – 100 %)</li>
                <li>Looks up the linked spool in the inventory. Note: lookup is performed by the spool's RFID
                    <code>tag_uid</code> only; the printer's <code>tray_uuid</code> is not used for automatic
                    matching.</li>
                <li>Calculates: <strong>new weight = Total Weight × remain / 100</strong></li>
                <li>If the difference from the current stored weight is ≥ 0.5 g, the inventory is updated</li>
            </ol>
            <p>
                Example: Your spool has a Total Weight of 1000 g. The AMS reports 75 % remaining.
                The app writes <strong>750 g</strong> to the inventory.
            </p>

            <h3>"Only Decrease" Mode (default ON):</h3>
            <p>
                This sub-option controls whether the sync can also <em>increase</em> the stored weight:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <strong>ON (default / safe)</strong> — The AMS can only lower the weight, never raise it.
                    Use this if you keep your records accurate manually and just want the AMS to
                    automatically subtract usage after each print.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>OFF (full two-way sync)</strong> — The AMS reading overrides the stored weight in
                    both directions. Useful to correct over-recording: if you accidentally subtracted too much
                    from a spool, putting it back in the AMS will restore the weight automatically once the
                    RFID chip reads a higher remaining value.
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h3>What Gets Updated — and What Doesn't:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>✅ <strong>Linked Bambu Lab RFID spools</strong> — updated automatically</li>
                <li>✅ Works across multiple AMS units if you have more than one attached</li>
                <li>❌ <strong>Non-tagged / third-party spools</strong> — never touched (no RFID = no UUID match)
                </li>
                <li>❌ <strong>Unlinked slots</strong> — ignored even if they have an RFID tag (you must link first)
                </li>
                <li>❌ Changes smaller than <strong>0.5 g</strong> are ignored to avoid excessive database writes
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Verifying It Works:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Go to the <strong>AMS</strong> page — each linked slot shows both <em>"AMS: X%"</em> and
                    <em>"Inventory: Yg"</em>. After a few seconds of connection the two figures should align.
                </li>
                <li>Open the filament in <strong>Inventory</strong> and check the spool weight — it should match
                    AMS% × Total Weight.
                </li>
                <li>Check the server console / Docker logs for lines like:<br/>
                    <code>AMS auto-update: spool 12 (Bambu Lab Plum) ▼ decreased 530g → 210g (AMS 21%)</code>
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Troubleshooting:</h3>
            <p><strong>Inventory weight never changes even though AMS sync is enabled</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Confirm the slot is linked — go to AMS page and check the "Linked to:" label</li>
                <li>Confirm the spool has a Total Weight set (0 g total = the calculated weight will always be 0)</li>
                <li>The RFID UUID stored on the spool must match what is saved in the inventory. Re-save the link on
                    the AMS page if in doubt
                </li>
                <li>Verify "Auto-update spool weight from AMS" is still checked after a page reload (Settings
                    persists it to the database — reload the Settings page and confirm)
                </li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Weight jumps up and down unexpectedly</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>The RFID chip reports in whole-percent steps, so a 1000 g spool has ~10 g resolution</li>
                <li>If "Only decrease" is OFF and the RFID reading occasionally fluctuates by 1 %, you may see
                    small up/down corrections — turn "Only decrease" back ON to prevent increases
                </li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>The spool weight jumped to a much higher value after I put a new spool in the same slot</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>The new spool has a different RFID UUID — it will only update the inventory if you link the new
                    spool on the AMS page first
                </li>
                <li>The old spool link is not automatically transferred to the new spool</li>
            </ul>

            <p>
                <em>💡 Pro tip: Leave "Only decrease" ON day-to-day. Turn it OFF temporarily only when you need to
                    correct an over-recorded spool, then turn it back ON after the correction has been applied.</em>
            </p>
        </div>
        @backToTop
    </div>

    <div class="formCard" id="mqttterminal" style="scroll-margin-top: 20px;">
        <h2 style="margin-top: 0;">📡 MQTT Message Log</h2>
        <div style="color: var(--muted); line-height: 1.8;">
            <p>
                The <strong>MQTT Message Log</strong> in Settings is a built-in diagnostic terminal that
                shows the last 50 raw JSON messages received from your BambuLab printer in real time.
            </p>

            <h3>How to Access It:</h3>
            <ol>
                <li>Go to <strong>Settings</strong></li>
                <li>Scroll down to the <strong>"📡 MQTT Message Log"</strong> card</li>
                <li>The terminal is visible whenever the printer is connected</li>
            </ol>

            <h3>What You See:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Timestamp</strong> - Time each message was received (HH:mm:ss), shown in blue</li>
                <li><strong>Topic</strong> - The MQTT topic (<code>device/report</code>), shown in green</li>
                <li><strong>Payload</strong> - The full raw JSON from the printer, shown in white</li>
                <li>Messages scroll automatically — newest message always at the bottom</li>
                <li>A maximum of <strong>50 messages</strong> are retained; older ones are removed automatically</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Controls:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>🔄 Refresh</strong> - Manually fetch the latest messages from the service</li>
                <li><strong>🗑️ Clear Display</strong> - Clears the on-screen list (does not clear the service buffer)
                </li>
                <li><strong>● Connected / ○ Not connected</strong> - Real-time connection status badge</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Use Cases:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Debugging AMS data</strong> - Verify that tray color, type, and sub-brand are being reported
                    correctly by the printer
                </li>
                <li><strong>Confirming connectivity</strong> - See messages flowing in real time to confirm the MQTT
                    link is live
                </li>
                <li><strong>Understanding printer state</strong> - Inspect raw gcode_state, temperatures, and layer info
                </li>
                <li><strong>Troubleshooting</strong> - If something looks wrong in the UI, check the raw messages to see
                    what the printer is actually sending
                </li>
            </ul>

            <p>
                <em>💡 Tip: The log auto-scrolls to the bottom on every new message. If you want to read older messages
                    without them scrolling away, use the 🗑️ Clear Display button to freeze the view, then re-enable with
                    🔄 Refresh when you're done.</em>
            </p>
        </div>
        @backToTop
    </div>

